            <Title>Pavlovian conditioning</Title>
            <Text>What it is
Upon hearing the term “Pavlovian,” almost everyone thinks of the famous experiment by Ivan Pavlov in which a dog was conditioned to expect food when a bell was rung. Eventually, the dog started salivating as soon as the bell rang, even if no food was present.
From birth, all animals and humans are equipped with a limited set of reflexes (i.e., genetically hard-wired responses to specific environmental stimuli). A reflex is the relationship between a specific environmental event or stimulus and a fixed behavioral action or response evoked by that stimulus. Because these reflexes are often critical to survival, they can affect our decision making fundamentally, often without our awareness.
#
Understanding the basic concepts of Pavlovian conditioning can help you resist potentially destructive behaviors.
￼
How it relates to investing
It’s not so surprising, then, to learn that investor behavior is often more instinctual than it initially appears. As we have already seen, one of our most basic tendencies is to “fit in” with our social group. This is one type of conditioned behavior focus investors must learn to avoid. Even though a majority of people utilize certain market strategies, it doesn’t mean these approaches are necessarily the right ones. Understanding the basic concepts of Pavlovian conditioning can help you resist these potentially destructive behaviors.
Pavlovian association is broken down into three basic classes: classical, instrumental and operant conditioning. Let’s have a look at each in greater detail.
Classical conditioning
Classic conditioning is when a repeated stimulus elicits the same conditioned emotional response over time. For example, imagine past visits to your grandmother’s home where it always seemed to reek of mothballs. Now every time you smell mothballs you recall visiting your grandma; this is one example of classical conditioning.
This closely relates to the concept of association. When you watch a Coca-Cola commercial, do you ever see the people drinking Coke not having a good time? Of course not! In its ad campaigns the soft-drink company deliberately (and successfully!) associates drinking Coca-Cola with good times and being happy.
Instrumental conditioning
Instrumental conditioning occurs when a behavior either is continued or discontinued as a result of positive or negative reinforcement received. Trademarks that have developed a positive image tend to generate positive thoughts among current and prospective consumers, which in turn create future sales opportunities.
The sheer strength of Pavlovian association is revealed when sales of a product increase even when it is priced higher than comparable products. One reason for this increase in sales is that most people associate higher prices with higher quality. Tiffany, for example, uses its brand appeal to price its products much higher than comparable products that lack the prestigious brand name.
Operant conditioning
Operant conditioning involves associative learning, in which there is a correlation between the response and the presentation of the reinforcer, or reward. This concept was introduced in the classic experiments by B. F. Skinner in which he trained rats and pigeons to press a lever in order to obtain a food reward. His experiments proved that behavior can be modified through the use of rewards.
Charlie Munger gives a powerful example of how a reward system can influence behavior when he discusses Xerox:
Early in the history of Xerox, Joe Wilson, who was then in the government, had to go back to Xerox because he couldn’t understand how their better, new machine was selling so poorly in relation to their older and inferior machine. Of course when he got there he found out that the commission arrangement with the salesmen gave a tremendous incentive to the inferior machine.
What to do
Be aware of your natural bias to be highly accepting of information that confirms your established thoughts or beliefs. Assume nothing; investigate everything!
When examining companies, consider these factors related to conditioned behavior:
	•	Do the company’s commercials create the appropriate feelings or images for their brand?
	•	Does the firm’s compensation package (i.e., stock options and other management perks) reinforce innovation—or stagnation?</Text>
