            <Text>Accounting is the language in which business results are reported. The ability to understand this language is an integral part of every investor’s toolkit. I recommend that focus investors have at least some training in accounting, whether in a classroom, online or from a high-quality book on the subject (see two suggestions below).
Having a basic understanding of generally accepted accounting principles (GAAP), the method accountants commonly use to prepare financial statements, is not enough for practitioners of focus investing. GAAP is a flexible system and, as such, allows company managers a certain amount of leeway in how they report their financial results. This flexibility is dangerous, as management can “play” the system to show better-than-actual results.
This subject of accounting is far too broad in scope to cover adequately in this book. To learn more about accounting red flags and pitfalls, I recommend Guide to Financial Reporting and Analysis by Eugene E. Comiskey and Charles W. Mulford, as well as Financial Shenanigans (2nd Edition) by Howard M. Schilit.
会计是报告业务结果的语言。理解这种语言的能力是每个投资者工具包的一个组成部分。我建议重点投资者至少在会计方面进行一些培训，无论是在课堂上，在线上还是从高质量的书上（见下面的两个建议）。
对于普遍接受的会计原则（GAAP）有一个基本的了解，会计师通常用来编制财务报表的方法，对于重点投资的从业人员是不够的。通用会计准则是一个灵活的系统，因此，允许公司经理在报告财务业绩方面有一定的回旋余地。这种灵活性是很危险的，因为管理层可以“发挥”系统来展示比实际结果更好的结果。
这本会计学的范围太广泛，足以在本书中涵盖。要了解更多关于会计危机和陷阱的信息，我推荐Eugene E. Comiskey和Charles W. Mulford的财务报告和分析指南，以及Howard M. Schilit的Financial Shenanigans（第二版）。</Text>
